---
description: PostgreSQL database and persistence rules (SQLAlchemy + Alembic)
globs: backend/app/models/**, backend/alembic/**, backend/app/dependencies/**
---

Database stack:
- PostgreSQL 16 as the source of truth for all structured application data.
- SQLAlchemy 2.0 (async) as the ORM.
- Alembic for schema migrations.
- AsyncPG as the async database driver.

Database rules:
- Design tables with clear ownership, timestamps, and constraints.
- Add indexes for common filters and joins (calls by lead, transcripts by call, predictions by lead).
- Use foreign keys where appropriate.
- Prefer soft-delete only when there is a real product need.

Schema design expectations:
- Every core entity should have: id (UUID), created_at, updated_at.
- Multi-tenant: include tenant_id on all tenant-scoped tables; enforce tenant isolation.
- Use enums or constrained fields for finite states (call_status, lead_status, user_role, etc.).
- Keep schemas normalized unless denormalization is justified by performance needs.
- Core entities per CLAUDE.md: tenants, users, leads, calls, call_transcripts, call_analyses, deal_predictions, campaigns, lead_flows, notifications, webhooks, audit_logs.

Migration rules:
- All schema changes must go through Alembic migration files.
- Never modify the database schema manually in production.
- Keep migration files small and focused (one migration per feature).
- Include both upgrade() and downgrade() in every migration.

Repository/data access rules:
- All DB access should use SQLAlchemy async sessions via dependency injection.
- Keep query code out of routes; use service + repository pattern.
- Parameterize queries; avoid N+1 query patterns (use joinedload, selectinload).
- Use transactions when multiple writes must succeed together.

Do not:
- Write raw SQL inside controllers/routes.
- Make schema changes without Alembic migration files.
- Assume single-tenant; scope queries by tenant_id.
- Hardcode database URL in code; use environment configuration.
